# Example site local.zeek for the c2-detection-ssl package.
#
# Copy the @load lines into your Zeek site local.zeek
# (usually /usr/local/zeek/share/zeek/site/local.zeek).
#
# The package is PRODUCTION-READY BY DEFAULT — production thresholds are
# already active with no tuning required. All site-specific tuning
# (allowlisted domains, proxy config, interception CA, VLAN exclusions)
# lives in scripts/local-exclusions.zeek inside the package, which is
# preserved across package upgrades. You normally do NOT put tuning here.

# ---- Activate the package ----
@load c2-detection-ssl

# Strongly recommended: early-warning tunnel detection on long-lived flows
# (otherwise a tunnel is only evaluated when the flow finally closes).
@load corelight/zeek-long-connections

# Optional: adds JA4 fingerprints to ssl.log (used for pivot detection).
@load foxio/ja4

# ----------------------------------------------------------------
# Deployment profile.
#
#   Production thresholds are the DEFAULT. Nothing to do for live use.
#
#   For replaying SHORT offline PCAPs (malware sandbox captures, a few
#   minutes of traffic) the production time/sample gates will suppress
#   real detections because the capture is too short. Load the sandbox
#   profile in that case ONLY:
#
#     @load c2-detection-ssl/sandbox
#
#   You may also @load c2-detection-ssl/production explicitly for clarity;
#   it is a no-op since production is already the default.
# ----------------------------------------------------------------

# ----------------------------------------------------------------
# Enable Zeek Notices (optional).
#
#   The package always writes c2_detections_ssl.log. Notices are OFF by
#   default so you can tune against the log first. Turn on once satisfied:
# ----------------------------------------------------------------
# redef C2_SSL::generate_notices = T;

# ----------------------------------------------------------------
# All other tuning -> scripts/local-exclusions.zeek
#
#   Proxies, interception CA, allowlisted domains, trusted subnets, and
#   device-VLAN exclusions all go there so they survive package upgrades.
#   See that file's header for the full explanation.
# ----------------------------------------------------------------
